            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XII.R4 </em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Pave the Merdle way</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-e0138301-7fff-213f-ab02-2e5a9da2bc0c\"><br />A version of this phrase appears three times in the Note for this number (see LD.XII.L2 and LD.XII.R12).&ldquo;The great Merdle!&rdquo; is invoked in this chapter as a reason to support Amy&rsquo;s wish to become acquainted with Pet (Mrs. Gowan), given the families&rsquo; connections. &ldquo;Mr. Merdle&rsquo;s is a name of&ndash;ha&ndash;world-wide repute,&rdquo; says Mr. Dorrit. &ldquo;Mr. Merdle&rsquo;s undertakings are immense. They bring him in such vast sums of money, that they are regarded as&ndash;hum&ndash;national benefits. Mr. Merdle is the man of this time. The name of Merdle is the name of the age&rdquo; (LD 468-69). Such effusive praise in the mouth of Mr. Dorrit implies that his praise may be misguided. </span></p>"
        }
    ],
